---
description: General coding standards
alwaysApply: true
---

- Use strong typing.
- Avoid `Any` and TypeScript `any`.
- Never use magic constants.
- Use named configuration and policies.
- Keep functions small and single-purpose.
- Keep modules cohesive.
- Use descriptive names.
- Prefer explicit data flow.
- Avoid hidden mutation.
- Avoid global mutable state.
- Avoid duplicated business logic.
- Do not swallow exceptions.
- Convert low-level exceptions at clear boundaries.
- Preserve original error context.
- Use structured error types.
- Use deterministic serialization where hashes or replay are involved.
- Use Decimal for financial values.
- Use timezone-aware timestamps.
- Store timestamps in UTC.
- Keep rounding policy explicit.
- Never leave TODOs, stubs or fake implementations.
- Prefer simple correct designs over clever abstractions.
